cards.desc:
**Average Wait Time ( AWT )**

‌

Average Wait Time, or AWT, is the average time a caller spends waiting to be routed to a contact center agent. It’s also referred to as the Average Speed of Answer (ASA).

‌

**calculate the average waiting time & average turn-around time**

![tdVcohVmPDBVUrY8JVzKw2KmGFdC6-2iltk5QWrbmiYWSNmwQnwS2bfFn9nyxqEUttWcBxaLCuQZTlYGbGKon1IFc6sReZaJ3kcq7Y0GMV-sejYNuOenmAW5x8uni-cLwCJjnyEUV51JUSNokvcMc64](https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/tdVcohVmPDBVUrY8JVzKw2KmGFdC6-2iltk5QWrbmiYWSNmwQnwS2bfFn9nyxqEUttWcBxaLCuQZTlYGbGKon1IFc6sReZaJ3kcq7Y0GMV-sejYNuOenmAW5x8uni-cLwCJjnyEUV51JUSNokvcMc64)

- Process Arrival Time* Burst Time

**Example:**

‌

Average turn-around time

= (6+7+11+16+13)/5

= 53/5

= 10.6

**Average turn-around time = 10.6**

‌

Average waiting time

= (0+5+6+10+12)/5

=(33)/5

=6.6

**Average waiting time =6.6**

‌

To calculate the average wait time in a cloud call system, you need to gather data on the wait times experienced by callers and then calculate the average based on that data. Here's a step-by-step guide on how to do it:

1. Collect Data: Start by recording the wait times of callers in your cloud call system. You need to note the time at which each caller enters the system and the time at which they are connected to a live agent or their call is resolved.
2. Calculate Wait Times: For each call, subtract the entry time from the connection/resolution time to determine the wait time for that specific call.
3. Sum the Wait Times: Add up all the individual wait times from step 2 to get the total wait time.
4. Count the Calls: Determine the total number of calls that were recorded during the data collection period.
5. Calculate the Average: Divide the total wait time (from step 3) by the number of calls (from step 4) to calculate the average wait time.

Formula: Average Wait Time = Total Wait Time / Number of Calls

For example, if the total wait time is 1000 seconds and there were 50 calls, the average wait time would be 20 seconds (1000/50 = 20).

**Sticky Agents:**
_**Case 1:**_ Normal Conditional if any Customer call on the DID number, then its goes to normal flow diagram, General IVR will play customer can choose as per their required department. Call will flow as per the condition set ( Condition 1, 2, or 3 )

_**Case 2: Sticky Agents**_
If any costumer calls on the DID number with sticky agent option enabled at the first time the first agent will be set as the sticky agent for that particular customer.And the next time the customer calls on the DID number the call will be forwarded to that same sticky agent.

_**Case 3: If Sticky Agents is Busy**_
If the Sticky agent is busy when call arrived, will be redirected to another voice call for sticky pipeline customer, so customer will have choice either to go with another available Agents or be on the Queue for the same Sticky Agents.

**Conditions:**
_**Condition 1: Serial wise in an order to all selected users**_
In this condition, within Agents section we must have priority setup on the basis call will flow. So priority 1, will get highest and likewise. So call will hunt agents based on setup priority to agents and if all agents busy call will be kept in queue once any of the agent is free, it will immediately assigned to FREE agents.

_**Condition 2: Balanced call distribution to all selected users:**_
In this condition, call is forwarded to all the agents without priority
If one agent is receives  more calls compared to other agent then the call priority is given to the agent with least number of calls.

_**Condition 3:**_\*\* Simultaneous calls to all selected users\*\*
In this condition, call is forwarded to all the agents without priority at the same time. Any agent who is free can attempt to receive the call.
